[[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major General]] '''Evelyn Edward Thomas Boscawen, 7th Viscount Falmouth''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|KCVO|CB}} (24 July 1847 – 1 October 1918) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Peerages in the United Kingdom|peer]] and [[British Army]] officer.

==Military career==
Boscawen was commissioned into the [[Coldstream Guards]]: he played cricket for the [[Household Division#United Kingdom|Household Brigade]] and then for the 1st Battalion Coldstream Guards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/885/885099/885099.html|title=Evelyn Edward Thomas Boscawen|publisher=Cricket Archive|accessdate=28 April 2014}}{{subscription required}}</ref> He fought in the [[Anglo-Egyptian War (1882)|Anglo-Egyptian War]] in 1882 and, having been promoted to colonel in 1886, he also took part in the Nile Expedition between 1894 and 1895.<ref name=burke>Burke's Peerage</ref> He was promoted to [[major-general]] in 1898 and became Assistant Military Secretary to the [[Commander-in-Chief, Ireland|Commander-in-Chief]], Ireland in 1900.<ref name=burke/> He was appointed a deputy lieutenant of [[Kent]] on 8 January 1900,<ref>{{London Gazette | issue=27154 |page=296 | date=16 January 1900}}</ref> and of [[Cornwall]] on 19 March.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27176 |page=1969 |date=23 March 1900}}</ref> He retired from the army on 9 August 1902.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27462 |date=8 August 1902 |page=5101}}</ref>

Boscawen succeeded to the title of 7th [[Viscount Falmouth]] on 6 November 1889.<ref name=burke/>

==Family==
He married Hon. Kathleen Douglas-Pennant on 19 October 1886.<ref name=burke/> Their daughter, Kathleen Pamela Mary Corona (1902–1995), the actress [[Pamela Carme]], married theatrical manager [[Henry Sherek]].<ref name="Darlington">{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36063|title=Henry Sherek|last=Darlington|first=W. A.|year=2004|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref>

According to [[Lady Randolph Churchill]]'s sisters, he could have had a liaison with her and so have been the biological father of [[John Strange Spencer-Churchill]], the younger brother of former Prime minister [[Winston Churchill]].<ref>Sebba, Anne. ''American Jennie: The Remarkable Life of Lady Randolph Churchill'', Norton, 2008</ref>

